  <section class="category-info-block">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>PCB Cleaning Machines &amp; Industrial Cleaners</h2>
      <p>A PCB cleaning machine removes surface particles from circuit boards before critical process steps. Dust, fibers, and static-bonded debris cause defects throughout production. Surface particles cause solder paste to adhere poorly during screen printing. Components shift during pick-and-place when the board surface is not clean. A well-specified circuit board cleaning machine removes these problems at the source. This improves yield and reduces rework costs long term.</p>

      <h3>Types of Industrial Cleaning Machines</h3>
      <p>DGSDK manufactures industrial cleaning machines for specific substrate types and production environments. Small to medium production lines and high-volume automated lines use different cleaning methods. The right machine depends on your substrate, line speed, and particle profile:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>PCB Cleaning Machines</strong> — Adhesive roller-based circuit board cleaners that remove surface particles from both sides of PCBs without chemicals or water. These are the most common cleaning methods for SMT pre-print and pre-placement positions.</li>
        <li><strong>SMT Inline Cleaning Machines</strong> — Fully automatic inline machines with PLC control, matching conveyor speeds in continuous SMT production. The SMT600 Series uses dual upper and lower rollers with integrated static removal.</li>
        <li><strong>FPC Cleaning Machines</strong> — Multi-axis precision cleaning systems for flexible printed circuits. Available in 4-axis and 8-axis configurations for different throughput requirements.</li>
        <li><strong>Optical Film Cleaning Machines</strong> — Large-format cleaning systems for optical films, polarizer sheets, and display substrates. Handles wide film widths without deformation or surface marking.</li>
        <li><strong>LCM Module Cleaning Machines</strong> — Industrial cleaning for liquid crystal modules before bonding, inspection, and packaging. Removes particles that cause optical defects in finished display units.</li>
        <li><strong>Backlight Panel Cleaning Machines</strong> — Precision cleaning for backlight units before assembly. Removes dust that causes bright spots and non-uniformity in finished panels.</li>
        <li><strong>CCL Cleaning Machines</strong> — Surface preparation cleaning for copper clad laminate boards before PCB manufacturing processes.</li>
        <li><strong>Inspection Stage Cleaning Machines</strong> — Positioned immediately before automated optical inspection (AOI) or manual inspection, reducing false rejects from surface debris.</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Adhesive Roller Cleaning Methods</h3>
      <p>Most DGSDK industrial cleaning machines use adhesive roller cleaning methods. Precision silicone or specialized adhesive rollers contact the substrate surface and lift particles by adhesion. This approach does not require compressed air, water treatment, or chemical waste management.</p>
      <p>The cleaning action is mechanical and consistent across every substrate that passes through the machine. Adhesive rollers transfer particles to a secondary paper roll or cleaning tape. Quick-change window structures allow roller and paper roll replacement in minutes. This minimizes line downtime and keeps cleaning performance stable long term, even in high-volume production environments.</p>
      <p>Adhesive roller cleaning is a dry process. It does not add moisture or chemicals to the substrate. This makes it safe for PCBs, optical films, polarizers, and other sensitive surfaces. The method works at production line speeds without slowing output.</p>

      <h3>Cleaning Solutions for Different Substrates</h3>
      <p>Different substrates need different cleaning approaches. Hard, rigid boards like PCBs and CCL can handle standard roller pressure. Flexible substrates like FPC boards need gentler contact to avoid deformation. Optical films and polarizer sheets need light, uniform contact to avoid surface marking.</p>
      <p>DGSDK designs cleaning solutions for each substrate type. PCB cleaning machines use rollers set for rigid board surfaces. FPC cleaning machines use multi-axis systems that hold the substrate flat during cleaning. Optical film cleaning machines use wide rollers with low contact pressure to clean the film without distortion.</p>
      <p>Choosing the right cleaning solution for your substrate type prevents damage and ensures effective particle removal. Our team can help match the right machine to your process.</p>

      <h3>Circuit Board Cleaning Machine vs. Manual Cleaning</h3>
      <p>Manual cleaning of circuit boards introduces variation. Human contact with board surfaces adds dirt from skin oils, static discharge, and uneven cleaning pressure. Manual cleaning also slows production throughput and increases labor costs.</p>
      <p>An automated circuit board cleaning machine delivers consistent performance at line speed. It removes the quality variation that manual cleaning introduces. The machine applies the same cleaning force and roller contact across every board.</p>
      <p>For production environments where yield and consistency matter, automated cleaning solutions replace manual cleaning at every critical process point. Automated cleaning also supports traceability and process control.</p>

      <h3>Cleaning Machines for Tight Spaces and Compact Layouts</h3>
      <p>Factory floor space is often limited. Not every production line has room for a large inline cleaning system.</p>
      <p>DGSDK offers compact cleaning machine designs that fit into tight spaces between existing process equipment. The <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/pcb-vertical-cleaner">PCB Vertical Cleaning System</a> uses a vertical substrate path to minimize the horizontal footprint. This makes it practical to install a circuit board cleaning machine in tight spaces where conventional horizontal machines would not fit.</p>
      <p>Compact cleaning solutions reduce the barrier to adding automated cleaning at any point in the production line.</p>

      <h3>Cleaning Machine Integration with Production Lines</h3>
      <p>DGSDK industrial cleaning machines integrate with existing production lines. Each machine matches the conveyor speed and height of the upstream and downstream equipment. This allows cleaning to be added at any point without stopping the production flow.</p>
      <p>Standard electrical and mechanical interfaces simplify installation. Most machines operate on standard power supplies. Control signals connect to existing PLC systems for synchronized operation. Line operators can monitor cleaning performance from the existing control panel.</p>
      <p>Cleaning machines can be positioned at multiple points in a line. Common positions include before screen printing, before pick-and-place, before optical inspection, and before final assembly. Adding a cleaning machine at each of these points gives the greatest improvement in yield.</p>

      <h3>Industrial Cleaning Machine Maintenance</h3>
      <p>Keeping industrial cleaning machines in good condition is simple. The main maintenance task is replacing adhesive rollers and paper rolls. Most machines use quick-change designs that allow replacement in minutes. Line downtime for roller changes is short.</p>
      <p>Roller replacement frequency depends on the particle load and production volume. High-volume lines with heavy particle loads require more frequent changes. Low-volume or low-particle environments need fewer changes.</p>
      <p>DGSDK provides replacement rollers, paper rolls, and spare parts for all cleaning machine models. Our service team supports customers with maintenance schedules, part availability, and on-site assistance when needed.</p>

      <h3>Choosing the Right Circuit Board Cleaning Machine</h3>
      <p>The correct circuit board cleaning machine depends on your substrate type, line layout, throughput, and particle profile. Different production environments need different cleaning solutions.</p>
      <p>For SMT production lines, the <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/smt-cleaner">SMT600 Series inline cleaner</a> integrates directly into the conveyor flow. For small to medium line layouts where floor space is limited, the <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/pcb-vertical-cleaner">PCB Vertical Cleaning Machine</a> offers a compact footprint. For FPC and film substrates requiring high-precision handling, the multi-axis <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/fpc-4-axis-cleaner">FPC 4-Axis</a> and <a href="/products/cleaning-machine/fpc-8-axis-cleaner">FPC 8-Axis cleaning machines</a> provide the substrate control needed to avoid deformation.</p>
      <p>Contact us with your substrate dimensions, line speed, and particle requirements for a configuration recommendation.</p>
